111	/**
112	 * Class that can be used to bootstrap and launch a Spring application from a Java main
113	 * method. By default class will perform the following steps to bootstrap your
114	 * application:
115	 *
116	 * <ul>
117	 * <li>Create an appropriate {@link ApplicationContext} instance (depending on your
118	 * classpath)</li>
119	 * <li>Register a {@link CommandLinePropertySource} to expose command line arguments as
120	 * Spring properties</li>
121	 * <li>Refresh the application context, loading all singleton beans</li>
122	 * <li>Trigger any {@link CommandLineRunner} beans</li>
123	 * </ul>
124	 *
125	 * In most circumstances the static {@link #run(Class, String[])} method can be called
126	 * directly from your {@literal main} method to bootstrap your application:
127	 *
128	 * <pre class="code">
129	 * &#064;Configuration
130	 * &#064;EnableAutoConfiguration
131	 * public class MyApplication  {
132	 *
133	 *   // ... Bean definitions
134	 *
135	 *   public static void main(String[] args) {
136	 *     SpringApplication.run(MyApplication.class, args);
137	 *   }
138	 * }
139	 * </pre>
140	 *
141	 * <p>
142	 * For more advanced configuration a {@link SpringApplication} instance can be created and
143	 * customized before being run:
144	 *
145	 * <pre class="code">
146	 * public static void main(String[] args) {
147	 *   SpringApplication application = new SpringApplication(MyApplication.class);
148	 *   // ... customize application settings here
149	 *   application.run(args)
150	 * }
151	 * </pre>
152	 *
153	 * {@link SpringApplication}s can read beans from a variety of different sources. It is
154	 * generally recommended that a single {@code @Configuration} class is used to bootstrap
155	 * your application, however, you may also set {@link #getSources() sources} from:
156	 * <ul>
157	 * <li>The fully qualified class name to be loaded by
158	 * {@link AnnotatedBeanDefinitionReader}</li>
159	 * <li>The location of an XML resource to be loaded by {@link XmlBeanDefinitionReader}, or
160	 * a groovy script to be loaded by {@link GroovyBeanDefinitionReader}</li>
161	 * <li>The name of a package to be scanned by {@link ClassPathBeanDefinitionScanner}</li>
162	 * </ul>
163	 *
164	 * Configuration properties are also bound to the {@link SpringApplication}. This makes it
165	 * possible to set {@link SpringApplication} properties dynamically, like additional
166	 * sources ("spring.main.sources" - a CSV list) the flag to indicate a web environment
167	 * ("spring.main.web-application-type=none") or the flag to switch off the banner
168	 * ("spring.main.banner-mode=off").
169	 *
170	 * @author Phillip Webb
171	 * @author Dave Syer
172	 * @author Andy Wilkinson
173	 * @author Christian Dupuis
174	 * @author Stephane Nicoll
175	 * @author Jeremy Rickard
176	 * @author Craig Burke
177	 * @author Michael Simons
178	 * @author Madhura Bhave
179	 * @author Brian Clozel
180	 * @author Ethan Rubinson
181	 * @author Chris Bono
182	 * @author Moritz Halbritter
183	 * @author Tadaya Tsuyukubo
184	 * @author Lasse Wulff
185	 * @author Yanming Zhou
186	 * @since 1.0.0
187	 * @see #run(Class, String[])
188	 * @see #run(Class[], String[])
189	 * @see #SpringApplication(Class...)
190	 */
191	public class SpringApplication {
